{"data":{"post":{"id":"2bb886d6-e421-55d2-b6a6-0e894db09d75","html":"<p>My friend Cristina, Pach, and I had a chance to attend a <a href=\"http://www.japansociety.org.uk/14016/iwc-award-winning-sake-tasting-at-the-japanese-embassy/\">sake-tasting event at the Japanese embassy</a> last Thursday and had fun drinking 14 of the award-winning sake (from the <a href=\"http://www.internationalwinechallenge.com/\">International Wine Challenge</a>). Despite our sake-newbieness, our favourite turned out to be the <a href=\"http://www.internationalwinechallenge.com/wine/150513/2011/Nabeshima-Daiginjo.aspx\" title=\"IWC Sake Winner\">IWC Trophy Champion for 2011</a> <strong>(Nabeshima Daiginjo, 2010).</strong> The judges of the International Wine Challenge describe it as <strong>“Soft with a sweet, fruity aroma. On the palate the flavours are dry, earthy and nutty with hints of fresh stone fruits. The finish is long with warming alcohol and lift.”</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Our palate needed some re-education on everything about sake</strong>. I’ve always thought sake should be served warm but we learned a special tidbit from a Japanese girl who told us that warm sake is a sign of low quality. </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/sake1__gdnnng-bc93183ef5b68f5b1704c2d0ab4bd46f-b0edb.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; null; max-width: 427px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 149.88290398126463%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"sake1  gdnnng\"\n        title=\"Sake-tasting event at the Japanese embassy. © Photo by Natsuki Pimienta Kikuya\"\n        src=\"/static/sake1__gdnnng-bc93183ef5b68f5b1704c2d0ab4bd46f-b0edb.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/sake1__gdnnng-bc93183ef5b68f5b1704c2d0ab4bd46f-f0558.jpg 200w,\n/static/sake1__gdnnng-bc93183ef5b68f5b1704c2d0ab4bd46f-4e4eb.jpg 400w,\n/static/sake1__gdnnng-bc93183ef5b68f5b1704c2d0ab4bd46f-b0edb.jpg 427w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 427px) 100vw, 427px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Sake-tasting event at the Japanese embassy. © Photo by Natsuki Pimienta Kikuya</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>For a more professional sake advise, our blogger friend slash sake sommellier <strong><a href=\"http://natsukipim.com\" title=\"Natsukipim\">Natsuki Pimienta Kikuya</a></strong> wrote a more in-depth post at her blog. She is organising a sake charity event to support the Japan earthquake victims on <strong>Sept 20 at the Japanese embassy</strong>. <strong>RSVP to kanpailondon@gmail.com</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/kanpai_sake_yns0vb-615a3225a3c0050d75fb869f45a510a6-15a1e.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 400px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 88.75%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"kanpai sake yns0vb\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/kanpai_sake_yns0vb-615a3225a3c0050d75fb869f45a510a6-15a1e.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/kanpai_sake_yns0vb-615a3225a3c0050d75fb869f45a510a6-e9677.jpg 200w,\n/static/kanpai_sake_yns0vb-615a3225a3c0050d75fb869f45a510a6-15a1e.jpg 400w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-55fd7.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; null; max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 66.71875%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Nabeshima Daiginjo hkc2hd\"\n        title=\"Fukuchiyo Shuzo. Table Mr. Iimori, champion Sake producer this year with his “Nabeshima Daiginjo, 2010. © Photo by Natsuki Pimienta Kikuya\"\n        src=\"/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-55fd7.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-e81c0.jpg 200w,\n/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-8e8ea.jpg 400w,\n/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-55fd7.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Fukuchiyo Shuzo. Table Mr. Iimori, champion Sake producer this year with his “Nabeshima Daiginjo, 2010. © Photo by Natsuki Pimienta Kikuya</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>Beyond the sushi and the sake wooziness, I stumbled upon a brochure from the <strong>Daiwa Foundation announcing its Foundation Art Prize which is open to all British artists who previously haven’t had any solo exhibition in Japan.</strong> The winning artist will receive a participation fee of 5000 pounds, travel and accommodation costs for a 7 day period in Japan plus assistance with introductions with key individuals in Japanese contemporary art. Open to all artists working in any medium. For more information check the Daiwa Foundation <a href=\"http://www.dajf.org.uk/grants-awards-prizes/daiwa-foundation-art-prize\" title=\"Daiwa Foundation website\">website</a>.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/Image463_dhnuqx-2d38fc96e15ceac95e3c5cacc61c836b-0dbaf.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block; ; max-width: 357px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 54.34173669467788%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Image463 dhnuqx\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/Image463_dhnuqx-2d38fc96e15ceac95e3c5cacc61c836b-0dbaf.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/Image463_dhnuqx-2d38fc96e15ceac95e3c5cacc61c836b-c30b9.png 200w,\n/static/Image463_dhnuqx-2d38fc96e15ceac95e3c5cacc61c836b-0dbaf.png 357w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 357px) 100vw, 357px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>Related Links:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/national/news/20110908p2g00m0dm033000c.html\" title=\"Nabeshima\">Saga’s Nabeshima chosen as champion sake at London wine competition</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nb20110909a3.html\" title=\"Nabeshima wins\">Saga tipple named champion sake at London blind wine-tasting event</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.hospitalityandcateringnews.com/2011/09/supermarkets-reign-supreme-in-the-iwcs-world-of-wine/\" title=\"Supermarkets reign supreme\">Supermarkets Reign Supreme in the IWC’s World of Wine</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nb20110909a3.html\" title=\"Nabeshima wins\">Nabeshima wins</a></li>\n</ul>","fields":{"slug":"/turning-japanese-sake-tasting-event-and-the-daiwa-foundation-art-prize-2011/","prefix":"12 September 2011"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Turning Japanese: Sake-Tasting Event and The Daiwa Foundation Art Prize 2011","category":"culture","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"resize":{"src":"/static/Nabeshima_Daiginjo_hkc2hd-9925006145060bc3cd53a840cf895381-d927d.jpg"}}}}},"authornote":{"id":"b6415c02-57f6-5889-8910-a05deb06efca","html":"<p>Article by <strong>Tuesday Gutierrez</strong>. Former digital marketing manager for the London 2012 Festival, the largest UK festival ever staged. This is her blog about contemporary art, design, film, photography and all that move her soul.</p>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/turning-japanese-sake-tasting-event-and-the-daiwa-foundation-art-prize-2011/","prev":{"id":"379b1785-524e-534f-88ca-8de6cea2aeef","fields":{"slug":"/israeli-art-takes-centre-stage-in-freedom-of-expression-true-colours/","prefix":"7 September 201